recipeing:
2-3 # tips, stew, eye beef, cut into strips
1-2 onions, cut in half then sliced into strips
2 T minced garlic 
3/4 C ketchup
2 T Worcestershire sauce
1 T brown sugar
2 t salt (I omit)
2 t paprika
1/4 t dry mustard
dash cayenne pepper
1 1/2 C water
3/4 - 1 box rotini pasta - cook according to package
recipeinst:
Brown meat with onion and garlic till no longer pink (don't drain liquid).
Add remaining ingredients and simmer 2 hours on very low heat.  Thicken if desired.
Serve with rotini.  Even better as leftovers.

recipeing:
16 	oz.		egg noodles (penn dutch broad noodles)
4			eggs, (lightly beaten, room temp)
8 	oz.		cream cheese (room temp)
1	cup		sour cream (room temp)
1	stick	butter (room temp)
1	teas.		salt
1	teas.		sugar
1	jar		apricot jam (12 oz. smuckers)
recipeinst: Cook noodles according to the directions on the package for 5 minutes.  Whip with a wire whisk the eggs, cream cheese, sour cream, butter, salt and sugar until very smooth.  Drain noodles but do not rinse.  Toss with the cheese mixture.  Pour into a 9 x 13  greased pan.  Heat the apricot jam and spread over the noodle mixture.  Bake 350 for 30 minutes uncovered, then another 20 or so covered.  This recipe really varies based on your oven.
recipehist: This is a family favorite that I always make on Easter.  Goes great with a ham.

recipeing:
1 1/2 C vanilla 0% Chobani yogurt
10 -- 3/4 inch-thick slices challah or brioche bread
3/4 C whole milk
4 large eggs
2T light brown sugar
1 tsp. cinnamon
1 tsp. vanilla extract
pinch salt
serve with fresh berries & maple syrup
recipeinst:
Arrange bread slices in a greased, 9-inch baking dish
Whisk together yogurt, milk, eggs, sugar, cinnamon, vanilla & salt
Pour over bread, cover pan with plastic wrap.
Chill overnight.
Bake at 375 until golden brown, 25-30 minutes.
Slice and serve warm with fresh berries & maple syrup.
recipehist: An excellent make-ahead brunch dish for family/friend gatherings.

recipetitle:
20 slices thin white bread
3 oz. blue cheese
8 oz. creamed cheese
1 egg
20 spears of cooked aspa
recipeing:
1.  Trim crusts from bread and use rolling pin to flatten slices slightly.
2.  Blend cheeses and egg to workable consistency and spread evenly on each slice.
3.  Place asparagus on top of spread and roll up.
4.  Press edge of bread to seal.
5.  Roll in melted butter.
* Freeze in foil or to serve immediately, cut into thirds and bake in 400 degree oven (15 minutes or until lightly browned).
A great party appetizer!

recipetitle: Steak Tips with a Chimichurri Sauce
recipeing:
For the Steak tips:
Steak tips ***this is key: DO NOT buy the steak tips that are already cut up for you. Buy the steak tips that are still in long strips***
Salt, Pepper, and EVOO

For the Chimichurri Sauce:
Equal parts of fresh parsley and cilantro, three cloves of garlic (or more to your
liking), Parmesan cheese, pine nuts (if desired)
recipeinst:
Sprinkle some salt and pepper on your nice strips of steak tips to season. Then drizzle on some olive oil to cover and marinate it for at least 10 minutes.

Next, get your frying pan nice and hot on a medium-high setting. It turns out beautiful when you use a cast iron pan with ridges in the middle to make grill marks. Place your marinated strips of meat on the hot pan. Depending on the thickness of the tips, sear each side for 2 minutes if you want it medium. When all sides are seared, that's when you can start cutting them into the size you want. This allowed all the juices to stay in! After they are cut, sear them for 2 minutes each of the sides that haven't been seared and that's it, they're almost ready for eating.

Now it's time for the sauce, Put all the sauce ingredients in a blender/food processor and pulse a few times to chop. Put on low speed and start drizzling in olive oil until it reaches your desired thickness. Add salt and pepper to taste. Yum!

Now you're ready for your steak tips with your chimichurri dipping sauce.

Want a try a Texas twirl?
Instead of just salt and pepper, marinate the meat in salt, black pepper, garlic powder, paprika,  Worcestershire sauce (2 tbsp), a handful chopped cilantro, and don't forget the EVOO.
recipenut: Who cares? It tastes so good!!!

recipeing:
3/4 lb fusili pasta
3/4 lb bow-tie pasta
1/4 cup olive oil
1 1/2 cup pesto
10 oz pkg of frozen chopped spinach, defrosted and squeezed dry  (I leave this out - not a fan!)
3 Tbls freshly squeezed lemon juice (or use lemon juice from the super market)
1 1/4 cup mayonnaise
1/2 cup shredded Parmesan cheese
1 1/2 cups frozen peas, defrosted
1/3 cup pignoli nuts (pine nuts), toasted
3/4 tsp salt
3/4 tsp ground pepper
3 cooked chicken breasts, sliced
recipeinst: Cook the pasta until each is al dente.  Drain and toss with olive oil.  Cool to room temperature.In a food processor fitted with steel blade, puree the pesto, spinach and lemon juice.  Add the mayonnaise and continue to puree.  Add pesto mixture to pasta, then add Parmesan cheese, peas, pignolis, salt and pepper.  Mix well.  Serve at room temperature.\nOK - I just stir the pesto and lemon juice together.  Then I add the mayo and stir some more.  Add the pesto to the pasta, add the other ingredients as in the directions.  I add the chicken and stir into the pasta mixture.  (I'm always looking for the short cut!)
recipehist: This recipe was given to me by my friend, Sue.  She's a great cook and reads lots of cookbooks, which I don't have time to do.  The recipe is originally from The Barefoot Contessa Parties! cookbook!
